3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates funding rates for BONK/USDT every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC, using the difference between perpetual price and spot index. The exchange's zero maker fee policy makes it particularly attractive for funding rate arbitrage strategies, as traders can enter positions without upfront trading costs. Funding payments are automatically debited or credited to trader accounts at each interval, with rates typically ranging from -2% to +2% during high volatility periods."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","BONK","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BONK's status as a popular Solana meme token creates frequent funding rate imbalances on MEXC, especially during trending periods when retail sentiment drives excessive long or short positioning. The combination of MEXC's aggressive listing strategy and zero maker fees provides early access to funding arbitrage opportunities before other exchanges establish deeper liquidity."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BONK/USDT on MEXC has shown extreme funding rate volatility, with rates frequently exceeding ±1% during major price movements or social media trends. During the initial BONK hype cycles, funding rates often remained positive for extended periods as retail traders maintained long positions, creating consistent arbitrage income for short sellers. The 8-hour interval system means traders can capture funding payments three times per day, with historical data showing the most extreme rates typically occurring during Asian trading hours when meme coin activity peaks. Rate divergences between MEXC and other exchanges often persist for 24-48 hours due to the platform's retail-heavy user base."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunity Analysis"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fee structure creates a significant cost advantage for funding rate arbitrage, as traders can establish delta-neutral positions without paying entry fees. The exchange's thinner order books mean funding rates often overshoot compared to Binance or OKX, creating arbitrage spreads of 0.5-2% per funding interval during volatile periods. Cross-exchange arbitrage works particularly well by shorting BONK perpetuals on MEXC when funding rates are extremely positive while holding spot BONK or going long on lower-rate exchanges. The key is timing entries during peak sentiment periods when retail traders pile into long positions, driving funding rates to unsustainable levels."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's questionable volume reporting and thinner liquidity pools present unique risks for BONK arbitrage strategies, particularly during market stress when bid-ask spreads can widen significantly. The exchange's limited regulatory compliance means traders should limit position sizes and maintain adequate margin buffers, as liquidation mechanisms may be less predictable than on tier-1 exchanges. BONK's high correlation with Solana ecosystem health adds systematic risk, as network issues or broader crypto market selloffs can trigger rapid position unwinding that overwhelms MEXC's order book depth. Traders should also monitor MEXC's financial stability and withdrawal processing times, as funding arbitrage requires reliable access to funds across multiple platforms."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"Why are BONK funding rates often higher on MEXC than other exchanges?","answer":"MEXC's retail-focused user base and aggressive listing strategy attract speculative traders who often maintain directional positions rather than hedged strategies. This creates persistent funding rate imbalances, especially for trending meme tokens like BONK where sentiment-driven trading dominates."},{"question":"How does MEXC's zero maker fee affect BONK funding arbitrage profitability?","answer":"Zero maker fees eliminate entry costs for establishing arbitrage positions, improving net profitability by 0.02-0.06% per trade compared to traditional fee structures. This is particularly valuable for funding arbitrage where margins can be thin and frequent position adjustments are required."},{"question":"What's the minimum position size for effective BONK funding arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"Given MEXC's order book depth, positions under $10,000 USDT notional can typically be executed without significant slippage. However, the thin liquidity means larger positions may face challenges during market stress, making position sizing critical for risk management."},{"question":"How reliable are MEXC's funding rate calculations for BONK/USDT?","answer":"MEXC uses standard 8-hour funding intervals with transparent rate calculations, though the exchange's spot index methodology may differ from tier-1 platforms. Traders should verify funding rates against multiple sources and monitor for any calculation anomalies that could affect arbitrage strategies."}]}]
